      <section name='chat'>

         <para number='1' comment='Hello - After briefing'>
         Brian is pleased to see you again, and wants to know what progress you have made.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Hello - First meeting'>
         Brian the zombie greets you. "Hello, %s," he says. "Thank you for agreeing to help us. Shall I explain exactly what our problem is?"
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='lab'>
         "The Count's laboratory is in the tallest tower of the castle. He needs the height for his experiments." Brian shudders at the thought. "Of course, the access to the tower is via a secret stairway; you'd never find it if you didn't know where to look."
         </para>

         <para number='4'>
         He explains that you need to go to the bedroom which Count Sinistre uses as his sleeping quarters, and search the fireplace. You'll find the way into the lab.
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Cellar/store room'>
         Brian explains, "You can access the store rooms in the cellar through another secret door." He rolls his eyes and mutters something about the Count being far too fond of hidden exits and entrances. "This time, it's in an old linen cupboard. Twist one of the brackets and a trapdoor will open."
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='Control room'>
         "That's the room from which the collars are controlled," Brian explains. "You will need to walk through the room with the production line - I know, it's pretty disgusting in there, but you just need to grit your teeth and do it because it's the only place from which you can shut off those collars."
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='Nomatch for Brian'>
         Brian frowns. "I don't have time to talk about trivial stuff like that," he says. "Things are really serious."
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='bye'>
         "Goodbye, %s," says Brian. "Do what you can. We're all counting on you."
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='Explain/problem'>
         "I know you're here on behalf of the Guild, to find out how Count Sinistre plans to sell commodities at silly prices. Well, I can tell you how. His methods are vile, and he must be stopped..." Brian is so filled with emotion that he cannot go on for a moment. Then he pulls himself together and continues to tell you what you need to know.
         </para>

         <para number='10'>
         "Sinistre is a brilliant scientist and inventor. He's also quite mad and has no morals whatsoever. He has discovered a way to bring the dead back to life and to turn them into his slaves. He's using them as workthings without having to pay them, or even to feed them or do any of the things planet-owners usually have to do to keep their populations happy and productive.
         </para>

         <para number='11'>
         "It's brilliant... but vile. That's how he can produce goods at such low prices." Brian turns away for a moment, then says, "It's a lot to take in, I know. You need a moment to appreciate the horror of it all. Shall I continue?"
         </para>

         <para number='12' comment='Continue'>
         Brian turns back to you and continues his briefing. "He gets his henchmen to dig up corpses from the graveyard and take them to his lab, where he does whatever it is that brings them back to... well, it's not life, so let's call it half-life, shall we?" He smiles a very bitter smile. "Then before the revived zombie comes fully back to its senses, the Count turns them into obedient slaves.
         </para>

         <para number='13'>
         "Occasionally, something goes wrong with the enslavement process, which results in a zombie that can think for itself. Like me, and Cedric who you met outside the castle, and there are a few others. We've formed a kind of zombie resistance movement, not that we are able to do very much. But most of the zombies are mindless workers, condemned to a life of being controlled by a madman.
         </para>

         <para number='14'>
         "I need your help - we need your help. Will you help us, please, %s?"
         </para>

         <para number='15' comment='Yes - no topic'>
         Brian looks at you in surprise. He wonders why you are saying yes, when he hasn't asked you anything.
         </para>

         <para number='16' comment='No - topic is help'>
         Brian looks sad. "I see. Well, there's nothing more I can say, then. I will have to hope somebody else comes along who is more willing than you are."
         </para>

         <para number='17' comment='No - topic is task'>
         Brian looks annoyed at your negative response. "Well, you aren't going to be able to help much if you don't want me to explain about the tasks you will need to complete."
         </para>

         <para number='18' comment='No - no topic'>
         Brian looks at you in surprise. He wonders why you are saying no, when he hasn't asked you anything.
         </para>

         <para number='19' comment='Help'>
         You agree to help Brian and he looks very pleased. "There are three things that need to be done," explains Brian. "The first task is to destroy whatever machine or process the Count uses to bring the dead back to life. Once that is done, you must find a way to free the enslaved zombies.
         </para>

         <para number='20'>
         And finally, the third task is to get word back to the Trading Guild about what Sinistre tried to do here, and make sure they will never, ever allow this planet to join the trading network."
         </para>

         <para number='21'>
         Brian strides around the room, leaving the odd gobbet of flesh behind him as he walks. "Do you want me to go into more detail about the tasks?"
         </para>

         <para number='22' comment='Task - machine is dead'>
         "Your second task," explains Brian, "Is to free my fellow zombies from their ghastly enslavement. They are controlled by means of slave collars that are put round their necks as soon as they become zombies. You will need to get into the control room, from where the collars broadcast their instructions."
         </para>

         <para number='23' comment='Task - machine not dead'>
         "Your first task," explains Brian, "is to put a stop to the Count's ghastly practice of bringing the dead back and turning them into zombies. I don't know exactly how he does it, but it takes place in his laboratory."
         </para>

         <para number='24' comment='Progress - unknown'>
         You don't have anything much to report to Brian, so you explain that you are still exploring the castle thoroughly because you don't want to miss anything. He looks a bit sceptical, and suggests you hurry up and find your way to the laboratory.
         </para>

         <para number='25' comment='Progress - machine1'>
         You tell Brian that you have found your way into the lab which contains what looks like the machine used to make zombies. He tells you that you need to destroy the machine, and suggests that if you haven't already, you figure should out how it works.
         </para>

         <para number='26' comment='Progress - machine2'>
         You tell Brian that you have switched on the machine and can see how it works, with lightning shooting down the rod and being passed through to the electrodes. He suggests that you find a way to short-circuit the machine, by using some wire to redirect the power from the rod into the guts of the machine itself somehow.
         </para>

         <para number='27' comment='Progress - machine3'>
         You tell Brian how you used some wire to redirect the power, but the wire burnt out. He suggests you try it again, this time with something a bit more heavy-duty - he is sure he remembers seeing some cable in the one of the storerooms.
         </para>

         <para number='28' comment='Progress - machine4'>
         You tell Brian that the cable almost did the trick, but that the join between the two cables needs to be insulated. He snorts in amusement. "Duct tape," he says. "It always comes down to duct tape, doesn't it? The universe would probably fall apart without it."
         </para>

         <para number='29' comment='Progress - control0'>
         Brian is delighted to hear that you have destroyed the zombie-making machine. "That's marvellous, %s," he says. "Now, you need to free my zombie brothers and sisters (and the neuter ones too of course) by getting into the control room."
         </para>

         <para number='30' comment='Progress - control1'>
         You tell Brian what you saw in the control room. "Well, clearly you need to find out how to use the computer," he says. "I am sure that's how the collars are controlled."
         </para>

         <para number='31' comment='Progress - control2'>
         You fill Brian in on your progress so far. "Oh, that's clever," he says. "I would never have thought to look under the keyboard for the password. Well, now you can use the computer, you should find out how to make it free the zombies. Maybe it has a manual or some kind of help function."
         </para>

         <para number='32' comment='Progress - otherwise...'>
         You tell Brian that you know how to free the zombies but that you need a collar to make the computer work properly. "Ah," he says. "I had a working collar once - I knew it might come in handy so I had it put in a safe place."
         </para>

         <para number='33' comment='Collar'>
         "I managed to get hold of a working collar a while ago," says Brian. "I thought it might be useful one day but I didn't feel happy keeping it anywhere close to me in case it affected me somehow, so I had one of the other free zombies put it in a safe place."
         </para>

         <para number='34' comment='Safe place'>
         Brian looks a little uncomfortable. "Yes, well, that's the problem - I don't know exactly where the collar is. I gave it to a zombie called Sephronia, and she assured me she would find somewhere to leave it, but then she was caught by the Count's henchmen and killed before she could tell me exactly where it was. She did sort of hint at the hiding place she had in mind, though.
         </para>

         <para number='35'>
         "What was it she said... ah yes, I remember. She said she would leave it in her own special place. I have no idea what that means; I hope you can work it out. Oh - she did emphasize the word 'leave' for some reason."
         </para>

         <para number='36' comment='Wire etc'>
         "There are some store rooms in the cellar where all kinds of old junk gets dumped. You can probably find what you need down there if you have a root around."
         </para>

         <para number='37' comment='Computer - has logged on'>
         "Well done for logging onto the computer," says Brian. "I would never have thought to look there for the password. Now you need to figure out how to use it."
         </para>

         <para number='38' comment='Computer - not logged on'>
         "I am pretty sure that computer is what controls the slave collars, so you need to find out how to use it," Brian says.
         </para>

         <para number='39' comment='Cedric'>
         "Poor Cedric isn't very bright," Brian confides. "He's not much use for anything except passing on the message to anyone who comes to the planet that they need to see me. I told him to stay outside the castle, because he is sure to be caught if he tries to come in again."
         </para>

         <para number='40' comment='Sephronia'>
         Brian looks sad. "Sephronia was a valuable member of the zombie resistance," he says. "She was the one who found out that the Guild were sending an investigator here to check out the planet's economy. She was killed by the Count's henchmen when they caught her trying to get a message to the Guild.
         </para>

         <para number='41'>
         "She was also my friend... the first of the resurrected zombies to avoid being enslaved, after me. I miss her."
         </para>

         <para number='42' comment='Count/sinistre'>
         Brian says, "Count Sinistre is the owner of this planet. He's a traditional mad scientist - doing what he wants to do with no regard for other people who might get hurt."
         </para>

         <para number='43' comment='Graveyard'>
         "The planet is well named, isn't it?" Brian comments with a wry smile. "We don't know how all the graves got onto the asteroid, but it's likely that the Count set things up like this so he would have a ready supply of corpses at hand for his experiments."
         </para>

         <para number='44' comment='Wedgewood'>
         "He's the investigating accountant the Guild sent here, but so far he hasn't been much use at all," Brian explains. "He blundered around in the graveyard a bit, died a few times, then just hung around near the landing pad waiting for someone else to show up. It's just as well you've taken over because if we had to rely on him we'd never get anything done."
         </para>

         <para number='45' comment='Resistance'>
         Brian tells you "We have to be very careful because if the Count discovers that we can think for ourselves, he has us destroyed. The castle is riddled with sensors that detect zombie movement where there isn't supposed to be any, so I am confined to this room. You won't be affected by that of course because you're still alive.
         </para>

         <para number='46'>
         "Occasionally one of us manages to sneak in and out of the castle but it's very dangerous, which is why I told Cedric to stay outside. Others have been caught, so what we can do is very limited."
         </para>

         <para number='47' comment='Hello - Met but not briefed'>
         Brian the zombie greets you. "Hello again, %s," he says. "You rushed off so quickly last time we met that I did not have a chance to tell you about our problem is. Shall I explain now?"
         </para>

         <para number='48' comment='Insulat'>
         You tell Brian you need something to insulate the cables, and he says, "Well I usually find duct tape is good for that kind of thing."
         </para>

