      </section>

      <section name='note'>

         <para number='1' comment='get post-it note'>
         The post-it note is attached to the side of the screen a lot more firmly than it looks, and you find it impossible to remove. It must be made with super-strength glue.
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='screen'>

         <para number='1' comment='Control room -1814 - basic desc'>
         The screen is one of those old-fashioned 2-D screens with a flat surface. Very outdated technology! There's a post-it note stuck to the edge.
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='slot'>

         <para number='1' comment='Full slot description'>
         The slot is about six inches long and an inch wide. It has a collar inserted firmly into it.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Empty slot description'>
         The slot is about six inches long and an inch wide - it's much too big for a standard data crystal or disk, so whatever is meant to be inserted into it has to be quite large.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='Put collar into slot - already'>
         There is already a collar in the slot, which fits snugly in the available space, so you could not jam a second one in there no matter how hard you tried.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='Insert collar'>
         You insert the collar into the slot. After a bit of jiggling, and trying it the other way around, it slides in and snaps firmly into place.
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Not carrying collar'>
         You do not have a collar.
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='Ex collar - it is in slot'>
         The collar is firmly seated in the slot on the side of the computer.
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='Not in slot'>
         I can't see any collar in the vicinity!
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='Get collar - it is in slot'>
         The collar is firmly inserted into the computer's slot; the force required to remove it might cause some damage, which wouldn't be a good idea.
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='Can t insert collar - not logon'>
         You try to insert the collar into the slot, but it won't go in. You look at the screen and find out why: it is flashing up an urgent warning that only authorized users are allowed to do that. After a few moments, the box asking for the password reappears.
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='type'>

         <para number='1' comment='type - version A - frankenstein'>
         The computer chimes with a mellow tone and the words 'password accepted' appear on the screen. After a few moments, they vanish and the screen goes blank except for a command line with a flashing cursor where the operator types in instructions.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Nomatch'>
         The computer makes a rude noise and the words 'password not accepted' appear on the screen in large red letters. After a few moments, they vanish, and the 'please enter password' box returns.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='type - version B - help'>
         A list of the commands scrolls up on the screen. Most of it is pretty incomprehensible, and it scrolls off the top fast, but you manage to spot the one command you need. To disable the collars the command is: UNLOCK COLLARS. Well, that sounds simple enough!
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='Unlock collars - no collar'>
         A warning message flashes on the screen in big red letters: 'Synchronization frequency required. Please insert sample collar into slot.'
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Success'>
         The computer makes a soft chime, and a message appears on the screen: 'Collars unlocked and deactivated.' You have done it! You can hear the sound of yelling and cheering coming from the processing room, and then Brian bursts in. "Thank you, oh thank you %s," he says. "You did it. You freed us all!"
         </para>

         <para number='6'>
         A horde of joyful zombies follow him in and hoist you onto their crumbling shoulders. They carry you out through a passageway you didn't know about and back outside the castle walls, where they deposit you gently. With excited cries about going off to have a party, they all vanish back inside again, leaving Brian to congratulate you once again on your success.
         </para>

         <para number='7'>
         "There is one last thing you must do for us," he says. "The Galaxy must know about the evil Count Sinistre and his nefarious plots. Tell Wedgewood, and he will tell the Guild, who in turn will ensure that Sinistre will never, ever be allowed to join the federation of trading planets.
         </para>

         <para number='8'>
         You have done a great thing here today. Now I am off to join the party, and then I'm taking all the zombies off to The Lattice where we will get work as extras in horror films." He grins a grin so enormous you are worried his face will fall off, and then shambles back inside the castle.
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='Nomatch'>
         The computer bleeps angrily at you - it doesn't recognize that command.
         </para>

      </section>

