   <category name='machine'>

      <section name='examine'>

         <para number='1' comment='Ex machine - basic desc'>
         The machine is huge, taking up a whole wall of the laboratory. It has some large valves attached to the top, some capacitors on the side, and the face is covered with dials and gauges which presumably mean something. There is a big red handle on the side, which must be how you operate the machine.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='additional desc - wire2'>
         The machine has a wire attached to it which goes up to the lightning rod on the roof above.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='cable2 and cable3'>
         The machine has a cable attached to it which goes up to the lightning rod on the roof above.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='dead'>
         The machine looks completely wrecked - the valves or capacitors or whatever they are have shattered, the front has been blown off, and acrid smoke drifts out of the inner workings - along with the occasional spark.
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='use'>

         <para number='1' comment='Use machine - dead'>
         You pull the handle down several times, but nothing happens because the machine is kaput - remember?
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Corpse is on slab'>
         You pull the handle down, and the machine starts to hum. Some of the dials light up, and the needles in the gauges move. A crack of lightning hits the lightning rod and surges down to the electrodes, shocking the corpse back into some semblance of life.
         </para>

         <para number='3'>
         Congratulations, you have just made a zombie. Welcome to the mad genius club! Unfortunately, as you attempt to pat yourself on the back, the resurrected corpse roars in pain and rage and breaks free of the leather straps. It leaps off the slab and seizes you, then snaps your neck with a sudden burst of violence.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='wire2'>
         You pull the handle down, and the machine starts to hum. Some of the dials light up, and the needles in the gauges move. A crack of lightning hits the lightning rod and surges down the wire into the machine itself.
         </para>

         <para number='5'>
         Unfortunately, before the power surge has a chance to do any damage, the wire burns out and disintegrates. You are going to need to find something more robust like some industrial cable.
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='cable2'>
