   <category name='mobiles'>

      <section name='wedgewood'>

         <para number='1' comment='Hello - first greeting'>
         "Hello, I'm Wedgewood," says the rumpled-looking man. He consults his clipboard for a moment. "You must be %s - Puckleberry told me to expect you. I know he briefed you on the background and explained why I am here on this ghastly planet." He gives a little shudder as he considers his situation.
         </para>

         <para number='2'>
         After a moment of forlorn contemplation, he continues. "Well, I've tried to find the information I was sent here to get, but I haven't got very far." Wedgewood sighs.
         </para>

         <para number='3'>
         "The planet seems to be one big graveyard - hence the planet name I suppose - and every time I tried to get through it, I blundered into an open grave and died. I did manage to figure out how to avoid the damn things, but frankly, I am not cut out for this kind of work so I called for help. I'm an accountant, not a famous adventurer like that fellow, what's his name - Michigan Smith.
         </para>

         <para number='4'>
         "No, I am not the right one for this mission, and I hope you are, and that you are going to help."
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Hello if greeted not briefed'>
         Wedgewood frowns at you, a look of disapproval on his lined face. "Well, hello again. You rushed off before I had a chance to brief you on the mission," he says.
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='Hello - has been brief'>
         Wedgewood seems pleased to see you, and somewhat relieved that you are still in one piece. "Oh good, %s, why don't you tell me how you are getting on?" You need to tell Wedgewood about your progress.
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='Mission/help/brief'>
         "It's a relief to have someone here who is more suited to dangerous exploration," says Wedgewood. He holds up one finger. "Firstly, you need to explore and find out as much as you can about this place. That means getting through the graveyard - fortunately, I can tell you how to do that safely.
         </para>

         <para number='8'>
         "There seems to be some kind of building on the other side of the graveyard but I couldn't make out what it is. So secondly," he gestures with a second finger, "Find out what the building is and whether you will be able to get into it, then come back to tell me how you get on. We'll make some more plans once we have more of an idea of the situation."
         </para>

         <para number='9'>
         "It's very misty in the graveyard," explains the accountant, "Making it hard to see where you are walking, which is why I kept blundering into those blasted graves. However, the last time I died I managed to figure out how to avoid them in future. They all seem to be freshly dug, so there is always a pile of earth or some disturbed soil nearby.
         </para>

         <para number='10'>
         "Avoid walking anywhere that looks like there has been digging or where the ground has been disturbed, or where there are heaps of soil, and you shouldn't die."
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='Progress - zombies freed'>
         You tell Wedgewood that you have succeeded in destroying Count Sinistre's machine to turn the dead into the undead, and freed the zombies. Wedgewood grabs your hand and shakes it vigorously. "Splendid work, %s, absolutely splendid," he says, and for the first time a smile breaks out on his face.
         </para>

         <para number='12'>
         "You have succeeded where I was not able. Puckleberry will be delighted. I will message him immediately with the good news. Go and see him to collect your reward."
         </para>

         <para number='13' comment='Progress - brian - met'>
         You tell Wedgewood that you have spoken to another zombie, Brian. He is not so shocked as when you told about Cedric - he must be getting used to the idea of intelligent zombies now! Wedgewood asks you whether you have any useful information from Brian, but you have to admit that you do not. He looks a little exasperated and suggests you go back and talk to Brian some more.
         </para>

         <para number='14' comment='Progress - brian - brief'>
         You tell Wedgewood all the things Brian told you, about Count Sinistre and his enslavement of the zombies. Wedgewood's jaw drops as he listens, then he shouts, "Of course, that's how he intends to sell his goods for such low prices. Good grief, what a despicable plan. He'll be about to undercut all his competitors - it could wreak havoc in the Guild."
         </para>

         <para number='15'>
         You mention that it's not too good for the zombies, either, and he looks startled. "Oh, yes, of course, the poor zombies, we must think about them too. Well, from now on, obviously you need to liaise closely with this Brian and do what he suggests to put a stop to the evil Count and his nefarious plans. I don't see that I can be of much help until you have done what Brian asks."
         </para>

         <para number='16' comment='Progress - cedric - unknown'>
         Wedgewood looks a little disappointed that you haven't discovered anything significant yet. "Oh well, I suppose you'd better go back and look around some more."
         </para>

         <para number='17' comment='Progress - cedric - met'>
         You tell Wedgewood that you saw a zombie, and he looks astonished. At first he doesn't seem to believe you - "A zombie? But that's absurd. There's no such thing. Have you been drinking, %s?" - but eventually you manage to convince him that you are not off your head at which point he starts to ponder what to do about it.
         </para>

         <para number='18'>
         "I suppose it must be dangerous, in which case you should kill it. Isn't that what one traditionally does, at least in the holos I have seen? Or maybe take it prisoner so we can extract information from it. But will it be able to talk?" Wedgewood really does seem to be out of his depth with this situation and is clearly not going to be much help.
         </para>

         <para number='19'>
         "Oh, I really don't know... I think you are going to have to decide for yourself how to proceed; this is not my area of expertise."
         </para>

         <para number='20' comment='Progress - cedric - captured'>
         You explain to Wedgewood that you tried to capture the zombie using a lasso made out of bandages. He is very impressed by your resourcefulness, but when you confess that it didn't work, he looks glum. "Well, if you haven't already tried to kill it, maybe that's the next step," he says doubtfully. "It's a shame you weren't able to catch it and make it talk."
         </para>

         <para number='21' comment='Progress - cedric - killed'>
         You tell Wedgewood about killing the zombie with a garden implement. "Good," he says, "That was very brave of you. I could never have done that. Of course, now we'll never know what it wanted - it's a pity we couldn't make it talk somehow..." This doesn't seem very helpful but clearly Wedgewood is now out of ideas.
         </para>

         <para number='22' comment='Progress - has talked to cedric'>
         You tell Wedgewood that you had a chat with Cedric, and he looks astonished. "It spoke to you? You actually had a conversation with the zombie? My word, that is quite amazing. Well done, %s, well done, it would never have occurred to me that the creature was intelligent. I hope he was able to tell you something useful."
         </para>

         <para number='23' comment='Castle - Knows about stone'>
         You tell Wedgewood that you know how to get into the castle, and he is pleased with your progress, but suggests you go back and explore some more until you find the information he needs about how the owner of the planet plans to sell his goods so cheaply.
         </para>

         <para number='24' comment='Doesn t know about stone'>
         You tell Wedgewood that there is a huge castle on the other side of the graveyard. "Ah, that must be the building I caught a glimpse of just before I plummeted into yet another of those graves," Wedgewood says, then mutters to himself, "Very dangerous, leaving them open like that, against health and safety regulations I am sure."
         </para>

         <para number='25'>
         He turns his attention back to you. "The information I need, about the economics of this blasted planet, are probably inside the castle, so the next part of your mission must be to find your way inside." He lifts a fourth finger, then thinks for a moment and goes back to finger number three.
         </para>

         <para number='26' comment='Bye'>
         Wedgewood says, "Goodbye, %s," and goes back to what he was doing before you arrived - pacing around in a circle looking worried.
         </para>

         <para number='27' comment='Nomatch'>
         Wedgewood wrings his hands and looks worried. "What? What was that? Can we keep focussed here please?"
         </para>

         <para number='28' comment='Brian'>
         "Brian does seem like a resourceful person... erm... zombie... whatever," says Wedgewood. "I think you need to do what he tells you and put a stop to Count Sinistre's plans."
         </para>

         <para number='29' comment='Resistance'>
         "It sounds like somebody needs to stand up to this Count," Wedgewood declares. "I am glad the zombie resistance now has you to assist it to reach its goals. I don't see that there's anything I can do to help, but you have my moral support of course."
         </para>

         <para number='30' comment='Cedric'>
         "A zombie with a name... what an extraordinary thing..." muses Wedgewood. "Although he doesn't sound all that bright so probably won't be much help. Maybe there are more of them about."
         </para>

      </section>

